Session Summary
Goal: Replace per-frame-only detection with cross-frame object tracking so the system can identify who is most important in a multi-person shot and commit to following them.

What was built:

The existing YOLO + MediaPipe detectors had no concept of identity across frames — each frame was processed independently. We added ByteTrack (already bundled in ultralytics) which assigns persistent integer track IDs to each person frame-to-frame, then scores each track on four signals: box area (0.35), face presence (0.25), time on screen (0.20), and center proximity (0.15).

5 files changed:

File	Change
detect_yolo.py	Added detect_bodies_tracked() and reset_body_tracker()
detect_mediapipe.py	Added get_face_boxes() helper
plan_video.py	Tracker runs every frame; 5 new fields written to JSON/CSV
track_subject.py	_detect_frames() now picks a focus track and locks the crop trajectory to that person
edit_planning.py	5 new read-only columns in the planning UI, with importance color-coded green/yellow/red
New fields in planning JSON/CSV/UI: num_tracks, focus_track_id, focus_importance, focus_has_face, focus_area_pct

One potential gotcha for next session: If model.track() throws an error, run pip install lapx — ByteTrack needs a linear assignment solver that isn't always installed by default with ultralytics.


Added 
Good question. ByteTrack does assign persistent IDs to all detected persons — but the planning output only saves the winner.

From the JSON/CSV, you get:

num_tracks — how many unique track IDs were seen in the segment
focus_track_id / focus_importance / focus_has_face / focus_area_pct — only for the top-scoring track
The per-track track_obs dict inside _segment_track_metrics() holds scores for every person, but after picking the focus track, the rest are discarded — the other IDs and their scores never make it into the output files.

So in the editor, if you see num_tracks: 4, you know there were 4 people with ByteTrack IDs in that segment, but you only see the data for the one that scored highest. The other three are invisible in the UI.

If you want P2/P3 data exposed (e.g. to pick an alternate focus manually), the change would be in _segment_track_metrics() in plan_video.py — instead of just returning the top track, it'd need to return a ranked list, and the JSON schema + editor table would need to show it. That's not currently implemented.





